SIMPLE: imperious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imperious
<hw>Im*pe"ri*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>imperiosus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>imp⟦eacute⟧rieux</ets>. See
<er>Imperial</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Commanding; ascendant;
imperial; lordly; majestic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A vast and
<xex>imperious</xex> mind.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Tilloison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Therefore, great lords, be, as your titles witness,⟦br⟧
<qex>Imperious</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Haughty; arrogant; overbearing; <as>as, an
<ex>imperious</ex> tyrant; an <ex>imperious</ex> manner.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>imperious</qex> man will work us all⟦br⟧
From princes into pages.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His bold, contemptuous, and <qex>imperious</qex> spirit soon made
him conspicuous.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Imperative; urgent; compelling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Imperious</qex> need, which can not be withstood.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Dictatorial; haughty; domineering; overbearing;
lordly; tyrannical; despotic; arrogant; imperative; authoritative;
commanding; pressing.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Imperious</er>,
<er>Lordly</er>, <er>Domineering</er>. One who is <xex>imperious</xex>
exercises his authority in a manner highly offensive for its spirit and
tone; one who is <xex>lordly</xex> assumes a lofty air in order to
display his importance; one who is <xex>domineering</xex> gives orders
in a way to make others feel their inferiority.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imperiously</ent>⟦br⟧
